You do, you do, it's a fact,
you do get a little bit.

233
00:16:20,925 --> 00:16:22,197
They don't think it's dangerous.

234
00:16:22,551 --> 00:16:23,970
What kind of magazines
do you like?

235
00:16:24,010 --> 00:16:26,560
My favorite magazine is Confidential.

236
00:16:26,590 --> 00:16:27,890
I read that all the time.

237
00:16:27,931 --> 00:16:30,092
Why do you like that?

238
00:16:30,142 --> 00:16:35,433
They've got a lot of the inside
stories on things like water pollution.

239
00:16:35,483 --> 00:16:38,272
It's pretty interesting.
I like to read up on that.

240
00:16:38,323 --> 00:16:41,662
A lot of things that the government
is concealing, you know?

241
00:16:41,692 --> 00:16:46,491
Fischer looked at the
world his own way. I mean,

242
00:16:46,531 --> 00:16:50,552
Bobby was not socialized,
the way the rest of us were.

243
00:16:50,582 --> 00:16:56,321
Every idea he had, virtually, he had
to come to, through his own thinking.

244
00:16:56,351 --> 00:17:01,881
In these days, he was unusual. But,
he hadn't gone off the deep end yet.

245
00:17:08,529 --> 00:17:11,922
Boxing champions have been coming
to the Catskill Mountains of New York

246
00:17:11,942 --> 00:17:14,144
for almost half a century
to get in shape.

247
00:17:14,193 --> 00:17:17,062
But does a chess champion
need to train physically?

248
00:17:17,585 --> 00:17:19,431
Take a look behind that window,

249
00:17:20,054 --> 00:17:23,057
into the training headquarters
of Bobby Fischer.

250
00:17:27,573 --> 00:17:31,272
<i>Championship chess is a
physically exhausting game.

251
00:17:31,396 --> 00:17:33,534
<i>More than just a test
of mind and will,

252
00:17:33,994 --> 00:17:36,274
<i>it is a contest
of physical endurance too.

253
00:17:39,211 --> 00:17:43,171
<i>Bobby is 29, and he lives
virtually a monastic life.

254
00:17:43,679 --> 00:17:44,406
<i>He lives alone,

255
00:17:44,636 --> 00:17:48,885
<i>always in hotel rooms that seem
barely larger than chessboards.

256
00:17:48,909 --> 00:17:51,759
<i>A lot of the time he won't
even answer his telephone.

257
00:17:51,789 --> 00:17:56,733
<i>The television set is his window on
the world, exercise is part of it.

258
00:17:57,933 --> 00:18:00,652
I'm a world class
Olympic-level coach.

259
00:18:00,692 --> 00:18:03,102
I'm also a world champion
in the bench press

260
00:18:03,586 --> 00:18:05,392
and I've trained a lot of celebrities.

261
00:18:05,444 --> 00:18:10,692
But no one can match the
fabulous Bobby Fischer.

262
00:18:10,751 --> 00:18:15,121
He was interested in the
human body, how it performed...

263
00:18:15,151 --> 00:18:17,701
and how it could be more productive.

264
00:18:18,992 --> 00:18:22,672
He said "I want you
to work on my grip.

265
00:18:22,711 --> 00:18:24,671
"You see this dynamometer?

266
00:18:24,711 --> 00:18:27,841
I want to squeeze this thing
all the way to the end".

267
00:18:27,880 --> 00:18:32,351
I said, "The world's strongest man
has not squeezed 100 kilograms".

268
00:18:32,381 --> 00:18:36,141
He said, "I'll squeeze
105". I said, "Why?"

269
00:18:36,170 --> 00:18:39,842
"When I shake that little Russian's
hand, I want him to feel it!"

270
00:18:42,242 --> 00:18:43,694
I started him off
with a little swimming,

271
00:18:44,551 --> 00:18:46,743
racquetball,
which we were quite good at.

272
00:18:47,502 --> 00:18:48,589
A little weight training.

273
00:18:51,274 --> 00:18:52,587
I said, repeat this after me,

274
00:18:53,522 --> 00:18:57,643
"I'm a winner! I'm a champion!
I'm not a loser!"

275
00:18:59,164 --> 00:18:59,943
And he says,

276
00:19:00,009 --> 00:19:02,597
"Why'd you put the loser thing
in there? You know I'm a champion".

277
00:19:05,849 --> 00:19:09,949
Bobby is probably the most interesting
person I've ever photographed.

278
00:19:11,891 --> 00:19:14,981
There he is.
There's Bobby.

279
00:19:15,011 --> 00:19:20,152
"I decided to hold my
breath like this, and... "

280
00:19:21,431 --> 00:19:24,202
You know, it was good
for his training.

281
00:19:24,243 --> 00:19:26,842
He was in training
for Spassky.

282
00:19:28,412 --> 00:19:30,311
He asked me what
other jobs do I do?

283
00:19:30,342 --> 00:19:35,611
And I told him, I'm, I've just
finished one on the New York Jets.

284
00:19:35,651 --> 00:19:38,281
"Jets?" He thought
that was marvelous.

285
00:19:38,322 --> 00:19:40,521
He thought... He wanted
to hear all about it.

286
00:19:40,551 --> 00:19:43,291
How they train, and he said,

287
00:19:43,321 --> 00:19:46,420
"You know, I've got to
train like that as well".

288
00:19:53,200 --> 00:19:55,730
And he didn't
mind anything I did.

289
00:19:57,439 --> 00:20:03,592
But it could have gone either way.
He treated everybody else quite awful.

290
00:20:03,612 --> 00:20:05,192
<i>Bobby Fischer
is a stubborn young man.

291
00:20:05,232 --> 00:20:10,061
<i>Sometimes he fights for principal,
more often just for himself.

292
00:20:10,100 --> 00:20:14,102
<i>He'll refuse to play a match
because his special terms aren't met.

293
00:20:14,815 --> 00:20:15,726
<i>And for the past month...

294
00:20:16,382 --> 00:20:19,488
<i>he's been giving fits
to the International Federation too.

295
00:20:19,512 --> 00:20:23,630
<i>Not enough money for the winner
of the world title, he says.

296
00:20:23,660 --> 00:20:25,660
There was
bidding on the match.

297
00:20:25,710 --> 00:20:29,801
And Iceland got it, I guess
because they put up the highest bid.

298
00:20:29,830 --> 00:20:33,140
And Bobby didn't want to play.
He said the country's too small.

299
00:20:33,170 --> 00:20:35,920
They don't have facilities,
they don't have communication.

300
00:20:35,972 --> 00:20:37,138
The International Chess Federation

301
00:20:37,514 --> 00:20:39,276
wants word by tomorrow morning
from Fischer

302
00:20:39,318 --> 00:20:42,089
on whether he's agreeable
to 24 games in Iceland,

303
00:20:42,300 --> 00:20:43,929
and Fischer is taking his time
answering.

304
00:20:44,402 --> 00:20:46,981
You, as President
of the Icelandic Chess Federation -

305
00:20:47,378 --> 00:20:49,252
are there times where you have
been tempted to say,

306
00:20:49,768 --> 00:20:51,483
"Let's forget all about it"?

307
00:20:51,691 --> 00:20:54,822
As you know, we are
organizing a chess match,

308
00:20:54,861 --> 00:21:01,670
and our only wish is to enrich
the chess world.

309
00:21:01,700 --> 00:21:03,505
They had all these lawyers

310
00:21:04,356 --> 00:21:07,471
and they were raising demands
all the time.

311
00:21:07,773 --> 00:21:08,990
But at the same time,

312
00:21:09,133 --> 00:21:14,350
it was never clear whether Fischer
would come to Iceland.

313
00:21:14,626 --> 00:21:19,132
The stumbling block, the
principal one was the prize money.

314
00:21:19,629 --> 00:21:23,799
And I said, we have already
settled the money question.

315
00:21:23,839 --> 00:21:27,289
And we will not be
ready to discuss that.

316
00:21:30,513 --> 00:21:34,852
There was a real possibility that
the match wouldn't take place.

317
00:21:34,872 --> 00:21:40,351
One has to remember with Fischer, that
he dropped out of tournaments before.

318
00:21:40,371 --> 00:21:43,861
This was no bluff
necessarily.

319
00:21:43,871 --> 00:21:48,240
He's going, he's not going, and
then he told me he was going.

320
00:21:48,300 --> 00:21:52,200
He moved quietly, put his
hands on my shoulders, and says,

321
00:21:52,220 --> 00:21:55,970
"I'm going to Iceland,
Harry". You know, it was...

322
00:21:55,999 --> 00:22:01,020
So, and the next thing I would read
in the paper would be, he's not going.

323
00:22:10,599 --> 00:22:13,352
But, Bobby wouldn't sign it.

324
00:22:15,211 --> 00:22:16,971
And then Bobby disappeared.

325
00:22:24,500 --> 00:22:26,231
<i>Boris Spassky,
the world chess champion,

326
00:22:26,251 --> 00:22:29,871
<i>came to Iceland twelve days before
the match, scheduled to start Sunday.

327
00:22:29,901 --> 00:22:32,620
<i>Spassky said he wanted time
to get used to the place,

328
00:22:32,670 --> 00:22:38,080
<i>without, incidentally, being
constantly molested by newsmen.

329
00:22:38,100 --> 00:22:41,579
<i>Bobby Fischer was also sensitive
about being photographed.

330
00:22:41,599 --> 00:22:43,969
<i>Sensitive to the point that
he kept not showing up.

331
00:22:50,881 --> 00:22:57,612
He was sitting in Pasadena,
California, and my job,

332
00:22:57,651 --> 00:23:03,041
my personal mission, was to
get Bobby to go to Iceland

333
00:23:03,070 --> 00:23:06,861
and play the World
Championship Match.

334
00:23:06,891 --> 00:23:12,601
But I didn't see any activity.
I didn't see any plane ticket.

335
00:23:12,631 --> 00:23:17,970
I said, "Bobby, I have to go
to New York. My dad is sick.

336
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:23,119
Let's travel together. You'll
be that much closer to Iceland".

337
00:23:23,139 --> 00:23:27,809
He said, "Yeah, I think that's a
good idea, travel with a friend.

338
00:23:27,849 --> 00:23:30,460
Yeah, okay".

339
00:23:30,480 --> 00:23:35,068
I was getting him closer
to where he had to go.

340
00:23:37,241 --> 00:23:39,462
We took him to
Kennedy airport.

341
00:23:39,492 --> 00:23:43,481
We were headed for the
Icelandic Airlines counter.

342
00:23:43,491 --> 00:23:49,371
Somehow a Daily News
photographer spied him.

343
00:23:49,401 --> 00:23:54,790
And Bobby started running. He wasn't
just running, he was sprinting.

344
00:23:54,820 --> 00:24:01,190
I turned around, and I stopped, and I
put my hands up. I didn't say anything.

345
00:24:01,230 --> 00:24:05,779
And Bobby kept running,
right out of the airport

346
00:24:05,820 --> 00:24:10,499
to the curbside limousine, and
got in, and left the airport.

347
00:24:11,468 --> 00:24:15,168
Where to? Nobody knew.

348
00:24:15,188 --> 00:24:20,901
It was only three days before
the scheduled start of the match.

349
00:24:20,951 --> 00:24:23,851
Chess history was
in the balance.

350
00:24:25,570 --> 00:24:29,540
I said, you can stay at my parents'
home in Douglaston, Long Island.

351
00:24:41,340 --> 00:24:43,370
I don't think
the bell works.

352
00:24:45,010 --> 00:24:46,590
It works.

353
00:24:47,759 --> 00:24:51,588
Hi,
where are you?

354
00:24:59,489 --> 00:25:02,008
Oh,
I need to know...

355
00:25:11,080 --> 00:25:12,563
Bobby was staying at Saidy's house

356
00:25:13,240 --> 00:25:16,175
and Saidy's father
was dying of cancer at the time.

357
00:25:16,249 --> 00:25:18,120
I don't know whether he told
you that, and they were...

358
00:25:18,172 --> 00:25:22,461
they were trying their best to get
Fischer on that plane to Iceland.

359
00:25:22,513 --> 00:25:28,379
At one point Saidy said, "You
know, uh, my father's dying".

360
00:25:28,419 --> 00:25:31,049
And Bobby says,
"That's okay, I don't mind".

361
00:25:31,080 --> 00:25:34,068
They could not dislodge
him from that house.

362
00:25:34,098 --> 00:25:37,019
This was probably the most
stressful week of my life.

363
00:25:37,059 --> 00:25:39,258
<i>- Are you Dr. Saidy?
- Yes I am.

364
00:25:39,278 --> 00:25:42,858
Mr. Fischer made it clear that he
would try to go to Iceland tonight.

365
00:25:42,897 --> 00:25:45,870
Did he express these thoughts
to you? -Made it clear to whom?

366
00:25:45,901 --> 00:25:49,101
We had talked to a few people, and
they had the impression he was going.

367
00:25:49,121 --> 00:25:51,863
Well, everybody can
have impressions,

368
00:25:51,915 --> 00:25:54,245
but the only person who knows
what Bobby Fischer is going to do

369
00:25:54,291 --> 00:25:55,716
is Bobby Fischer.

370
00:25:55,740 --> 00:25:57,280
That's about all
I really want to say.

371
00:25:57,290 --> 00:26:01,751
- I see...
- I want you to all keep cool.

372
00:26:01,781 --> 00:26:05,501
At one point, during
his stay at our home...

373
00:26:05,550 --> 00:26:08,919
he simply said, "It's
over, I'm not going".

374
00:26:12,478 --> 00:26:14,009
Still no
sign of Bobby Fischer.

375
00:26:14,059 --> 00:26:15,929
Today, the International
Chess Federation

376
00:26:15,959 --> 00:26:18,850
postponed by 48 hours the start
of the match, but it said...

377
00:26:18,899 --> 00:26:23,649
if Fischer is not in Iceland by noon
on Tuesday, he will be disqualified.

378
00:26:23,689 --> 00:26:27,438
Mr. Thorarinsson,
if I may ask, are you worried?

379
00:26:30,361 --> 00:26:31,952
No.

380
00:26:31,982 --> 00:26:34,250
And, I just wondered if
you've ever seen Mr. Fischer,

381
00:26:34,280 --> 00:26:36,700
if you have any proof
that he actually exists?

382
00:26:39,650 --> 00:26:42,590
That's a good question.

383
00:26:42,620 --> 00:26:49,060
Yes, I think, gentlemen, we can agree
on the point that Mr. Fischer exists.

384
00:26:49,100 --> 00:26:51,929
We were losing
the whole thing.

385
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:57,218
We had to get Fischer
to come to Iceland.

386
00:26:57,270 --> 00:26:59,421
The Soviet Union had the feeling that

387
00:27:00,184 --> 00:27:03,918
the World Chess Champion
was humiliated.

388
00:27:05,048 --> 00:27:09,818
They wanted to call Spassky
back to the Soviet Union.

389
00:27:09,848 --> 00:27:15,720
Boris said to me, "This
is a very severe situation.

390
00:27:15,760 --> 00:27:19,331
You have to solve this
on a higher level".

391
00:27:19,361 --> 00:27:22,080
Gudmundur Thorarinsson,

392
00:27:22,130 --> 00:27:28,750
I think he asked the Prime Minister
of Iceland to call Kissinger.

393
00:27:28,790 --> 00:27:31,032
Fischer was very reluctant to go

394
00:27:31,704 --> 00:27:36,074
and I placed a call to him
and I said to him... go.

395
00:27:36,889 --> 00:27:38,829
The United States of America

396
00:27:39,273 --> 00:27:43,855
wanted Bobby to go there
and win the world title.

397
00:27:44,168 --> 00:27:49,067
By that time, James Slater,
the British multi-millionaire,

398
00:27:49,108 --> 00:27:51,467
had already
doubled the purse.

399
00:27:51,508 --> 00:27:57,511
So, Fischer's answer to Kissinger
was, "Yes, I've decided to play".

400
00:27:59,082 --> 00:28:02,500
What finally did
make you decide to go then?

401
00:28:02,540 --> 00:28:05,300
I feel that the prestige of
this country is at stake.

402
00:28:05,339 --> 00:28:08,170
Some people have suggested
this was psychological warfare,

403
00:28:08,209 --> 00:28:09,680
against Spassky on your part.

404
00:28:09,710 --> 00:28:13,409
- Mmm.
- Did that figure into it?

405
00:28:13,429 --> 00:28:15,079
No, huh-uh.

406
00:28:15,099 --> 00:28:18,098
I don't believe in psychology,
I believe in good moves.

407
00:28:23,719 --> 00:28:26,309
<i>Bobby Fischer
left New York for Iceland,

408
00:28:26,358 --> 00:28:31,148
<i>and what a scene that was on
the morning of July the 4th.

409
00:28:31,198 --> 00:28:34,318
Nothing like this has ever
happened in Iceland before.

410
00:28:34,367 --> 00:28:38,100
You try to describe the impact
on the citizens here at Reykjavik,

411
00:28:38,121 --> 00:28:41,040
is probably about the same as
if the promoters of the next,

412
00:28:41,080 --> 00:28:43,396
Joe Frasier-Muhammad Ali
prize fight,

413
00:28:43,709 --> 00:28:46,816
decided to stage their
international extravaganza

414
00:28:46,830 --> 00:28:48,780
in Butte, Montana.

415
00:28:48,800 --> 00:28:52,000
One observer said the chess match
was turning into the biggest thing,

416
00:28:52,050 --> 00:28:54,170
to hit Iceland,
since Eric the Red.

417
00:28:54,220 --> 00:28:56,259
Though some people were
still mad at Fischer,

418
00:28:56,289 --> 00:28:59,729
others approve of his
hold-out for more money.

419
00:28:59,758 --> 00:29:02,800
Well, he was fighting for all the chess
players of the whole world, I think.

420
00:29:02,810 --> 00:29:06,898
He's tedious, he's arrogant,
he's inconsiderate.

421
00:29:06,928 --> 00:29:10,138
Uh, basically, people think that
there's something wrong with the man.

422
00:29:36,758 --> 00:29:39,349
I became
his private bodyguard.

423
00:29:39,379 --> 00:29:42,190
It was a big moment
for me, you know.

424
00:29:42,219 --> 00:29:45,519
I was more of his
friend than a bodyguard.

425
00:29:45,558 --> 00:29:49,608
He was quite a
character, you know.

426
00:29:49,638 --> 00:29:55,528
He could be gentle, but he could
be like a volcano sometimes.

427
00:29:55,568 --> 00:30:00,038
And it was better to know when to
speak and when to keep quiet, actually.

428
00:30:02,736 --> 00:30:06,031
Finally Bobby
showed up in Iceland.

429
00:30:06,040 --> 00:30:09,999
Now, is he gonna really play
for the World Championship?

430
00:30:13,031 --> 00:30:15,799
It's been a long
road for Fischer to this game,

431
00:30:15,839 --> 00:30:18,590
and it'll be a long match
at the end of that road.

432
00:30:18,640 --> 00:30:23,039
Both he and Spassky
have to play 24 games.

433
00:30:23,059 --> 00:30:27,328
The match could last up to two
months, each game runs to five hours.

434
00:30:27,358 --> 00:30:31,478
The most intellectually exhausting
battle known to the mind of man.

435
00:30:31,489 --> 00:30:33,438
The World Chess Championship.

436
00:30:39,277 --> 00:30:42,657
We had the Icelandic Government,
the Icelandic President,

437
00:30:42,697 --> 00:30:48,170
the Ambassador of the Soviet Union,
the Ambassador of the United States,

438
00:30:48,201 --> 00:30:50,400
and many foreign guests.

439
00:30:50,449 --> 00:30:53,569
The theatre was full.

440
00:30:53,589 --> 00:30:56,580
<i>Regularly scheduled programs
will not be seen at this time,

441
00:30:56,590 --> 00:30:59,428
<i>so we may bring you the
following sports special.

442
00:30:59,459 --> 00:31:03,769
<i>ABC Sports presents the World
Chess Championship Match,

443
00:31:03,798 --> 00:31:07,767
<i>between Boris Spassky, the defending
champion from the Soviet Union,

444
00:31:07,798 --> 00:31:12,228
<i>and 29-year-old Bobby Fischer, the
challenger from the United States.

445
00:31:12,258 --> 00:31:13,858
It was the Super Bowl.

446
00:31:13,889 --> 00:31:18,477
The audiences were gigantic.
People stayed home from work.

447
00:31:18,528 --> 00:31:22,268
People were lining up in front
of TV sets at department stores.

448
00:31:22,288 --> 00:31:23,938
There were chess groupies.

449
00:31:23,948 --> 00:31:29,759
In Time Square, they were showing
the game live. It was that important.

450
00:31:29,789 --> 00:31:31,190
<i>Let's find out from you Larry...

451
00:31:31,230 --> 00:31:33,136
<i>If there are any
late-breaking developments.

452
00:31:33,188 --> 00:31:35,042
<i>They might fuss around
with the chess pieces

453
00:31:35,065 --> 00:31:36,864
<i>and the size of the board
and the lighting,

454
00:31:36,888 --> 00:31:41,448
<i>but I'm fairly confident
the match will start on time.

455
00:31:41,469 --> 00:31:47,289
Boris Spassky, the world chess champion
was there with all his assistants.

456
00:31:48,648 --> 00:31:52,298
But, Fischer was not here.

457
00:31:54,397 --> 00:31:58,298
<i>The clock has now been started. It
was officially 5:00 in Reykjavik.

458
00:31:58,318 --> 00:32:02,408
<i>Spassky is obviously anxious about
the whereabouts of Mr. Fischer.

459
00:32:05,247 --> 00:32:08,147
Bobby was
nowhere to be seen.

460
00:32:09,317 --> 00:32:12,029
And all of us despaired.

