00:49:05,334 --> 00:49:06,738
but also it could have
been captured by a bishop,

689
00:49:07,224 --> 00:49:09,173
and he would have had
a very ugly-looking...

690
00:49:09,213 --> 00:49:12,664
double pawn way over on
the side of the board, which,

691
00:49:12,684 --> 00:49:15,183
it was very
unaesthetic, let's say.

692
00:49:16,554 --> 00:49:18,774
<i>Uh, Frank, I can see Spassky.

693
00:49:25,735 --> 00:49:29,065
Uh, more tense than
you've seen him? <i>-Yes.</i>

694
00:49:31,905 --> 00:49:34,074
He may be... what?

695
00:49:34,125 --> 00:49:35,376
I see.

696
00:49:47,713 --> 00:49:51,583
Spassky did not find
the best continuation,

697
00:49:51,633 --> 00:49:55,673
and was consistently
outplayed...

698
00:49:55,703 --> 00:50:01,714
until Fischer won his first
game of his life against Spassky.

699
00:50:01,734 --> 00:50:02,933
He was on the scoreboard.

700
00:50:10,775 --> 00:50:11,995
What do you think
of Bobby Fischer?

701
00:50:12,026 --> 00:50:13,745
I like him.
I like his style.

702
00:50:13,775 --> 00:50:15,866
- Are you following the games?
- Yes I am.

703
00:50:15,896 --> 00:50:18,284
The American chess players
are behind Bobby 100%,

704
00:50:18,335 --> 00:50:22,534
and they're all anxious to see him
get in there, and win the championship.

705
00:50:24,574 --> 00:50:25,585
Do you think that Fischer

706
00:50:25,784 --> 00:50:28,180
will win for the first time
over the Russian champion?

707
00:50:28,475 --> 00:50:31,174
I think Fischer will win,
because he's playing for $200,000,

708
00:50:31,213 --> 00:50:32,390
but if Spassky wins

709
00:50:32,442 --> 00:50:35,138
most of the money will go
to the Russian government.

710
00:50:36,354 --> 00:50:39,803
People sat in bars betting on what
the next move was going to be...

711
00:50:39,853 --> 00:50:43,473
the way people bet on whether there is
going to be a hit in a baseball game.

712
00:50:43,523 --> 00:50:45,573
That's when chess really exploded.

713
00:50:51,646 --> 00:50:55,615
Tell me what, what, you know what
turns you on about chess. -What?

714
00:50:55,655 --> 00:50:57,786
Do you hope to be as good
as Bobby Fischer one day?

715
00:50:57,826 --> 00:51:01,704
Well, I'd hope to, but I
doubt if I would be. -Why?

716
00:51:01,744 --> 00:51:05,464
Well, I just think Fischer's just
about the best player in the world,

717
00:51:05,495 --> 00:51:08,745
and not very many people can
get to be as good as he is.

718
00:51:10,715 --> 00:51:15,224
We're watching the looming presence
of Boris Spassky and Bobby Fischer,

719
00:51:15,253 --> 00:51:20,174
as sketched by Leroy Neiman, noted
artist and familiar face to Wide World.

720
00:51:20,517 --> 00:51:23,005
Leroy is here with me
at the Wide World studio in New York

721
00:51:24,168 --> 00:51:24,946
and he's going to be

722
00:51:25,281 --> 00:51:28,213
sharing some of his artistic
impressions with us, in just a minute.

723
00:51:28,237 --> 00:51:29,090
Larry,

724
00:51:29,225 --> 00:51:30,769
I thought going up there
to that chess match

725
00:51:30,868 --> 00:51:32,376
would be like watching
the grass grow,

726
00:51:32,400 --> 00:51:34,984
but it was far more exciting
than I ever expected it to be.

727
00:51:35,008 --> 00:51:36,806
Well, I thought it was
pretty exciting too.

728
00:51:36,826 --> 00:51:40,164
It was just like the
Ali-Frasier fight all over again.

729
00:51:40,194 --> 00:51:43,584
This is Bobby Fischer leaving
the hotel for the fight,

730
00:51:43,614 --> 00:51:46,874
like a matador leaving the
Palace hotel in Madrid.

731
00:51:46,925 --> 00:51:52,294
On stage, the tension is
developing, it's a real "prizefight".

732
00:51:52,324 --> 00:51:54,424
That's when Fischer...
That's when he's a fighter.

733
00:51:54,464 --> 00:51:58,184
This right hand is, like it
struck and drew blood on Spassky.

734
00:52:14,814 --> 00:52:19,504
The score was even. Two
and a half, two and a half.

735
00:52:19,534 --> 00:52:22,835
Spassky
was not himself.

736
00:52:22,875 --> 00:52:27,544
All these shenanigans had
affected him adversely.

737
00:52:27,574 --> 00:52:30,684
He was not playing
his true game.

738
00:53:13,694 --> 00:53:16,754
They believed that
the chairs had been wired,

739
00:53:16,794 --> 00:53:22,163
and the lighting fixture, to
destabilize Boris' concentration.

740
00:53:22,193 --> 00:53:24,002
That's when Boris cracked.

741
00:53:25,663 --> 00:53:31,723
Spassky complained that
there was some radiation...

742
00:53:31,752 --> 00:53:33,563
which was affecting him.

743
00:53:33,592 --> 00:53:38,146
During the match I felt myself
quite unusually like before.

744
00:53:38,196 --> 00:53:42,905
So, that was reason to be for
myself... I'm not a suspicious man...

745
00:53:42,935 --> 00:53:45,254
to become suspicious.

746
00:53:46,625 --> 00:53:48,724
There might be something
in the chair.

747
00:53:48,754 --> 00:53:52,074
There might be something
on the surface of the chair.

748
00:53:52,114 --> 00:53:54,914
There might be
something in the light.

749
00:54:02,503 --> 00:54:05,223
They inspected the
chairs and the lights to see

750
00:54:05,252 --> 00:54:09,343
whether the Americans were up
to some kind of "hanky panky".

751
00:54:09,393 --> 00:54:12,933
They found two dead
flies, and that was it.

752
00:54:22,375 --> 00:54:25,195
Games 6 is very celebrated.

753
00:54:25,245 --> 00:54:31,114
It is probably the most reprinted
game of the entire match.

754
00:54:31,155 --> 00:54:36,205
It was like... a symphony
of placid beauty.

755
00:54:39,054 --> 00:54:41,014
Right on
the first move...

756
00:54:41,043 --> 00:54:46,342
Bobby Fischer came up with a
major surprise to the entire world.

757
00:54:46,383 --> 00:54:50,382
He almost always starts
the game, with moving

758
00:54:50,433 --> 00:54:54,772
the pawn in front of his
king, two pawns up, with E4.

759
00:55:10,825 --> 00:55:13,745
And in this game,
everybody's shocked.

760
00:55:13,794 --> 00:55:18,444
He started with the English
opening by playing C4.

761
00:55:18,483 --> 00:55:21,754
Spassky's preparation
was out the window.

762
00:55:23,224 --> 00:55:26,474
I'm sure he prepared for
many things, but not this.

763
00:55:27,843 --> 00:55:30,713
Fischer did not
play his usual game.

764
00:55:30,723 --> 00:55:32,498
He played a different kind of game,

765
00:55:32,652 --> 00:55:37,384
a placid, positional,
slowly building up game,

766
00:55:38,402 --> 00:55:43,553
where he deprived
Spassky of mobility.

767
00:55:43,572 --> 00:55:49,695
Pushed him back where his
pieces could not do anything.

768
00:55:49,735 --> 00:55:53,784
It was just a, just
a beautiful game...

769
00:55:53,834 --> 00:55:55,713
I don't know what more
can be said about it.

770
00:55:55,866 --> 00:55:57,962
It's just a model of precision.

771
00:55:58,704 --> 00:56:01,175
It was such a beautiful game,

772
00:56:01,204 --> 00:56:05,844
that when the crowd applauded
at the end of the game,

773
00:56:05,873 --> 00:56:12,462
Spassky, himself, stood up
and applauded Fischer.

774
00:56:12,502 --> 00:56:15,404
On his way back to
the hotel, Fischer said,

775
00:56:15,433 --> 00:56:16,903
"Did you see what
Spassky did?"

776
00:56:16,943 --> 00:56:20,242
He said "That's a sportsman.
He's a real sportsman".

777
00:57:27,673 --> 00:57:31,215
Game 21
reached move 40,

778
00:57:31,264 --> 00:57:33,682
the move at which the game
was adjourned,

779
00:57:34,001 --> 00:57:36,873
for the two players to go
and study it.

780
00:57:53,671 --> 00:57:57,075
<i>This is NBC nightly
news, Friday September 1st.

781
00:57:57,106 --> 00:57:57,801
Good evening.

782
00:57:58,025 --> 00:58:00,783
We'll have more on the developments
in the Watergate Bugging case.

783
00:58:01,296 --> 00:58:02,457
We'll hear George McGovern

784
00:58:02,567 --> 00:58:05,813
talking about tightening up
his campaign organization.

785
00:58:05,837 --> 00:58:08,091
And we'll have a look at the new
unemployment figures,

786
00:58:08,373 --> 00:58:09,818
but first Bobby Fischer.

787
00:58:09,973 --> 00:58:14,003
Today was the day when Fischer and
the Russian champion, Boris Spassky,

788
00:58:14,043 --> 00:58:18,012
were to have finished the 21st
game of the World Championship,

789
00:58:18,042 --> 00:58:19,869
a game they started yesterday.

790
00:58:19,921 --> 00:58:22,998
But Spassky, after what must
have been an agonizing night

791
00:58:22,999 --> 00:58:26,859
spent analyzing his position,
didn't even show up to play.

792
00:58:31,372 --> 00:58:35,812
I was going to photograph
Spassky in the morning.

793
00:58:35,841 --> 00:58:39,344
He comes straight over to
me, shook my hand, and said,

794
00:58:39,384 --> 00:58:42,403
"There is another
world champion.

795
00:58:42,413 --> 00:58:46,523
His name is Robert
James Fischer".

796
00:58:46,553 --> 00:58:50,045
I went back to the loft
later to Bobby's room,

797
00:58:50,094 --> 00:58:54,393
and I told him
Spassky just retired.

798
00:58:54,433 --> 00:58:58,962
And I want to be the
first to congratulate you.

799
00:58:59,012 --> 00:59:02,683
Congratulations, how you feel,
babe? Tell us how you feel about it!

800
00:59:02,723 --> 00:59:04,602
You said you were gonna do it.

801
00:59:04,643 --> 00:59:06,893
Listen, would you
talk to us, Bobby?

802
00:59:08,143 --> 00:59:10,391
Bobby, roll the window down!

803
00:59:12,981 --> 00:59:14,701
Bobby wanted
to get away...

804
00:59:14,731 --> 00:59:17,452
'cause they're all banging
on the door and all that,

805
00:59:18,522 --> 00:59:20,854
just to beat it
out into the hills.

806
00:59:23,924 --> 00:59:29,593
Someone brings up The New York Post,
and it says, "Bobby is the Champ".

807
00:59:46,855 --> 00:59:48,589
His mother had said to him,

808
00:59:48,738 --> 00:59:51,322
when she saw she couldn't
separate him from chess.

809
00:59:51,346 --> 00:59:54,285
She said, "Okay, go play chess.

810
00:59:54,854 --> 00:59:56,752
"When that's over, you
can start your life.

811
00:59:57,438 --> 00:59:59,361
You can do something important".

812
01:00:01,890 --> 01:00:05,664
<i>NBC news correspondent Dick
Schapp was in Iceland today...

813
01:00:05,704 --> 01:00:07,674
<i>and here's what Fischer said.

814
01:00:07,704 --> 01:00:09,824
How does it feel now, you
have the World Championship.

815
01:00:09,843 --> 01:00:13,153
You're the best in the world at
what you've devoted your life to.

816
01:00:13,173 --> 01:00:15,422
How does that feel inside?

817
01:00:15,463 --> 01:00:18,593
It feels pretty good, yeah. I mean,
my goal now is play a lot more chess.

818
01:00:18,634 --> 01:00:20,684
I feel I haven't played
enough chess.

819
01:00:34,393 --> 01:00:37,282
How did it feel... all this
between the mayor and all...

820
01:00:37,312 --> 01:00:38,861
Did you ever thought
of anything like that?

821
01:00:38,901 --> 01:00:41,821
No, I never, you know, thought
this was gonna happen...

822
01:00:41,851 --> 01:00:45,241
You know, with chess. I just
hope, uh, this keeps on.

823
01:00:47,130 --> 01:00:50,964
I just had a premonition that something
awful was going to happen to him.

824
01:00:51,246 --> 01:00:53,583
I didn't know what it would be,

825
01:00:53,632 --> 01:00:56,033
but I didn't feel
good about it.

826
01:00:56,053 --> 01:00:59,748
One of Fischer's problems
was that after the match,

827
01:00:59,923 --> 01:01:04,843
he was, supposedly, better known
by the population of the world,

828
01:01:04,923 --> 01:01:07,563
than anyone, except for Jesus Christ.

829
01:01:07,593 --> 01:01:11,491
And, he was a guy who
treasured his privacy.

830
01:01:12,402 --> 01:01:14,032
He had a problem.

831
01:01:25,481 --> 01:01:29,051
<i>The entire world knows the
name Bobby Fischer by now.

832
01:01:31,924 --> 01:01:34,923
Was it a letdown after it
was all over Bobby? I mean...

833
01:01:34,953 --> 01:01:36,953
Well, there must have
been a tremendous, uh...

834
01:01:37,013 --> 01:01:40,842
There was. I woke up the day
after the thing was over and...

835
01:01:40,882 --> 01:01:43,793
I just felt different. Like...

836
01:01:43,853 --> 01:01:46,413
something had been
taken out of me.

837
01:01:59,852 --> 01:02:05,022
He didn't really, after he won, know
what he wanted to do with his life.

838
01:02:05,052 --> 01:02:08,241
He, uh, he reached an end
point, when he was 29.

839
01:02:08,271 --> 01:02:12,213
He's 29 years old, and
he hadn't had a childhood.

840
01:02:17,604 --> 01:02:24,253
Is it not true that, um, the
chess masters are always young men,

841
01:02:24,292 --> 01:02:27,223
and that they...
they don't last?

842
01:02:27,263 --> 01:02:30,463
Uh, that's been true, generally
speaking, but there are exceptions.

843
01:02:30,483 --> 01:02:33,461
Steinitz, he was 63 when
he was world champion.

844
01:02:33,481 --> 01:02:35,762
But, you're in a fortunate
position, because...

845
01:02:35,802 --> 01:02:39,681
most of us in life, no matter
how successful we think we are,

846
01:02:39,731 --> 01:02:43,402
we still have to do what other people
want us to do, just to hold jobs.

847
01:02:43,441 --> 01:02:46,661
But, you don't have to hold a job...
You're on your own. -That's right.

848
01:02:46,691 --> 01:02:48,081
It's a unique position.

849
01:02:48,111 --> 01:02:50,280
That's right, you can't say
"Well, if Fischer won't come,

850
01:02:50,310 --> 01:02:54,370
we'll get some other chess genius,
uh, who's the best in the world".

851
01:02:58,144 --> 01:03:01,013
Bobby Fischer, the world champion
chess player,

852
01:03:01,043 --> 01:03:02,633
has until midnight tonight

853
01:03:02,840 --> 01:03:06,554
to decide whether to abide
by the international rules of chess,

854
01:03:06,683 --> 01:03:08,212
or give up his title.

855
01:03:08,262 --> 01:03:11,502
If Fischer defaults, the title
would go to the challenger,

856
01:03:11,522 --> 01:03:14,801
Soviet grandmaster,
Anatoly Karpov.

857
01:03:14,841 --> 01:03:20,271
He wanted probably to play
the kid from Russia, Karpov,

858
01:03:20,312 --> 01:03:24,281
and beat him. I mean, it
would be an easy task.

859
01:03:24,311 --> 01:03:30,282
On the other hand, part
of him knew he could lose.

860
01:03:30,321 --> 01:03:33,450
And, that's death to Bobby.
He didn't want to risk that.

861
01:03:33,490 --> 01:03:39,463
So, what came out was a series
of new demands on the rules.

862
01:03:39,493 --> 01:03:42,912
First of all, I like to
play matches without draws.

863
01:03:42,962 --> 01:03:46,803
And, uh, they're gonna have to increase
the prizes, if they want me to play...

864
01:03:46,843 --> 01:03:49,173
Well, if I get a title... They want
me to play a match for the title.

865
01:03:49,203 --> 01:03:52,543
I'm not gonna just play for
what their minimum prizes are.

866
01:03:54,142 --> 01:03:57,852
Accepting all of Fischer's
demands, was unacceptable

867
01:03:57,882 --> 01:04:00,353
politically for the
Soviet Chess Federation.

868
01:04:00,382 --> 01:04:03,821
<i>Barring a very unlikely last-minute
change of heart by Fischer,

869
01:04:03,851 --> 01:04:07,551
<i>Anatoly Karpov becomes the
new champion by default.

870
01:04:07,571 --> 01:04:11,732
The world chess body gave him
about 95% of what he wanted,

871
01:04:11,742 --> 01:04:15,960
but that was it. He
didn't defend his title.

872
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:22,073
I think he was unable to cope
with his own invincibility.

873
01:04:22,094 --> 01:04:25,542
He got more or less
scared to sit down again,

874
01:04:25,572 --> 01:04:29,042
in front of the board,
and risk losing.

875
01:04:29,082 --> 01:04:33,952
But only he who never
plays, never loses.

876
01:04:35,532 --> 01:04:39,442
We all felt disappointed
that he let chess down,

877
01:04:39,472 --> 01:04:42,141
he'd let the American
masters down.

878
01:04:44,191 --> 01:04:46,480
Yeah, we all felt
kind of a betrayal.

879
01:04:46,531 --> 01:04:50,711
<i>Whereas others
could suffer from a...

880
01:04:50,751 --> 01:04:52,822
<i>depression after such debacle.

881
01:04:52,851 --> 01:04:56,701
I went out to California
on a job, phoned Bobby,

882
01:04:56,741 --> 01:04:58,017
picked him up in Pasadena,

883
01:04:58,176 --> 01:05:02,500
where he was staying,
some cult place he was staying.

884
01:05:03,041 --> 01:05:06,538
<i>I've had so many bad experiences...

885
01:05:06,590 --> 01:05:08,895
And, he would talk
about nuclear disarmament,

886
01:05:10,802 --> 01:05:14,171
our capabilities, ICBMs, and that.

887
01:05:14,313 --> 01:05:18,642
You know? And that would go on
for about an hour and a half.

888
01:05:18,682 --> 01:05:22,181
<i>Just what is, the
Worldwide Church of God?

889
01:05:22,212 --> 01:05:26,580
Bobby had been involved with
the Church of God, since 1962.

890
01:05:26,619 --> 01:05:30,741
And after he won the Championship, the
church was providing him with a place.

891
01:05:30,770 --> 01:05:33,021
The Worldwide Church
of God was a...

892
01:05:33,071 --> 01:05:39,159
a group of people that believed in
fundamental principles of the Bible.

893
01:05:39,199 --> 01:05:41,780
Some people would probably
call us fundamentalists.

894
01:05:41,821 --> 01:05:44,080
That will bring on
the great tribulation!

895
01:05:44,120 --> 01:05:46,842
And that will end in the
second coming of Christ,

896
01:05:46,872 --> 01:05:48,874
the end of this
present civilization!

897
01:05:48,922 --> 01:05:53,092
Basically, a sense that there
was an impending coming Christ,

898
01:05:53,133 --> 01:05:56,462
and we need to prepare for
that particular second coming.

899
01:05:56,514 --> 01:05:58,283
I told him,
"It's all a bunch of hooey".

900
01:05:58,805 --> 01:06:02,430
But, uh, that's what he chose to do.

901
01:06:02,622 --> 01:06:06,791
<i>I've warned you may be living
in the time in which you will see...

902
01:06:06,832 --> 01:06:09,431
I went to his apartment
in Pasadena.

903
01:06:09,461 --> 01:06:11,701
It seemed to me pretty hopeless.

904
01:06:13,830 --> 01:06:16,271
He was extremely depressed.

905
01:06:16,468 --> 01:06:19,380
We would get into these long
discussions about the Bible.

906
01:06:20,716 --> 01:06:22,114
"Why are we here?"

907
01:06:22,138 --> 01:06:25,610
"What are we doing
here? What is life?"

908
01:06:27,450 --> 01:06:31,082
That's when he
started to go haywire.

909
01:06:31,121 --> 01:06:34,642
He, uh, felt that he was being
influenced by these Russians,

910
01:06:34,672 --> 01:06:40,122
and he also was scared of the
Mossad, Israeli Secret Police.

911
01:06:43,600 --> 01:06:47,432
He felt that he could be easily
spied upon through radioactivity.

912
01:06:47,521 --> 01:06:50,721
And through other
means, fillings...

913
01:06:50,741 --> 01:06:52,850
He thought maybe the Russians
could send signals there.

914
01:06:52,890 --> 01:06:54,440
Phones...

915
01:06:54,490 --> 01:06:57,361
Tinfoil, over
the windows...

916
01:06:57,390 --> 01:07:02,511
